{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5e096c3f-708a-4025-b1c3-001654aa3036","content":"Good news — `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` **still exist** on the `Application` class in .NET MAUI and work the same way.\n\nHowever, MAUI also introduces **Window lifecycle events**, which are now the preferred approach:\n\n```csharp\n// In App.xaml.cs\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created += (s, e) => { /* replaces OnStart */ };\n    window.Resumed += (s, e) => { /* replaces OnResume */ };\n    window.Stopped += (s, e) => { /* replaces OnSleep */ };\n    window.Destroying += (s, e) => { /* cleanup */ };\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Key differences:**\n- Window events are per-window (MAUI supports multi-window on some platforms).\n- Additional events available: `Activated`, `Deactivated`, `Backgrounding`.\n- For **platform-specific** hooks, use `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs`.\n\nIf you only need simple app-wide lifecycle handling, your existing overrides will still work with no changes.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0093d8a5-9203-4dad-9194-55535d78af6f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` in your `Application` subclass. In .NET MAUI, the equivalent approach uses the `Window` lifecycle events or the `ILifecycleBuilder` in `MauiProgram.cs`.\n\nSpecifically:\n- The `Application` class in MAUI still has `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` — they were not removed. However, the recommended MAUI approach is to use **Window lifecycle events** or **platform-specific lifecycle events**.\n\n\n- MAUI's `Window` class provides more granular control with events like `Created`, `Resumed`, `Activated`, `Deactivated`, `Stopped`, and `Destroying`.\n- For platform-specific lifecycle handling, you can use `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs` to hook into native lifecycle events.\n\nSo the straightforward answer is that `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` still work in MAUI, but the framework encourages using Window lifecycle events for better control and a more modern approach.","outputTokens":691},"id":"7d677b4b-3ddd-4d65-aa3f-dfbea0a2e512","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:45:34.123Z","parentId":"da0ee833-1762-4dfa-a1ce-1fe42afb4942"}
